04561nam a22005535i 9780226278766DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014049393  a9780226278766  a(DE-B1597)523655  a(OCoLC)915941114  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJC71b.K37 2015 4aJC71b.K37 2016 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a321.072231 aKastely, James L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rhetoric of Plato's Republic :bDemocracy and the Philosophical Problem of Persuasion /cJames L. Kastely. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Republic: Plato’s Democratic Epic -- t2. The Elenchic Victory and the Failure of Persuasion -- t3. Glaucon’s Request for a Persuasive Argument -- t4. Confronting Obstacles to Persuasion -- t5. The Limits of Persuasion: The Residual Force of Culture and the Unruliness of Desire -- t6. The Argument for Philosophy -- t7. A Rhetorical Account of Philosophy -- t8. Compelling a Philosopher -- t9. A Genuinely Persuasive Defense of Justice? -- t10. The Rhetorical Office of Poetry -- t11. Philosophical Rhetoric -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPlato isn’t exactly thought of as a champion of democracy, and perhaps even less as an important rhetorical theorist. In this book, James L. Kastely recasts Plato in just these lights, offering a vivid new reading of one of Plato’s most important works: the Republic. At heart, Kastely demonstrates, the Republic is a democratic epic poem and pioneering work in rhetorical theory. Examining issues of justice, communication, persuasion, and audience, he uncovers a seedbed of theoretical ideas that resonate all the way up to our contemporary democratic practices. As Kastely shows, the Republic begins with two interrelated crises: one rhetorical, one philosophical. In the first, democracy is defended by a discourse of justice, but no one can take this discourse seriously because no one can see—in a world where the powerful dominate the weak—how justice is a value in itself. That value must be found philosophically, but philosophy, as Plato and Socrates understand it, can reach only the very few. In order to reach its larger political audience, it must become rhetoric; it must become a persuasive part of the larger culture—which, at that time, meant epic poetry. Tracing how Plato and Socrates formulate this transformation in the Republic, Kastely isolates a crucial theory of persuasion that is central to how we talk together about justice and organize ourselves according to democratic principles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric) 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric). 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aplato, republic, rhetoric, democracy, persuasion, philosophy, nonfiction, justice, communication, audience, socrates, epic poetry, values, virtue, polis, transformation, political engagement, desire, will, city, authority, citizens, agency, argument, community, conversation, athens, dialogue, discourse, eros, education, good, ethics, freedom, liberty, consent, glaucon, heroism, inquiry, interlocutor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226278766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226278766/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deG